President Biden will sign an Executive Order today to establish the White House Task Force on Worker Organizing and Empowerment. The Task Force, chaired by Vice-President Kamala Harris and vice-chaired by Secretary Marty Walsh, will mobilize the federal government's policies, programs, and practices to empower workers to organize and bargain with their employers. It will include more than twenty cabinet members and heads of federal agencies. The decline in union membership in the United States has contributed to economic inequality, stagnant wages, and the shrinking of the middle class. The Task Force aims to address these issues by making recommendations on how existing policies can promote worker organizing and collective bargaining, as well as identifying new policies and regulatory changes needed. Vice-President Harris and Secretary Walsh will lead the Task Force, which will engage with leaders in the labor movement, academia, and advocacy groups to seek ideas and feedback. The Task Force has four goals: